In sum, run-differential says more about the quality of team than does
win-loss record because, especially early on in the season, win-loss
record can be skewed based on chance. Hence, a teamâ€™s 162-gameÂ win-loss
record is best explained by a combinationÂ of runs scored, runs allowed,
and luck.</p>

<p>Keri pointed out that this is about the time of the season when we can
start trusting run differential to tell us about the quality of a team.
Russell A. Carleton illustrates why this is
soÂ <a href="http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=23497">here</a>,
though his more advanced calculation, which employsÂ <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cronbach's_alpha">Cronbachâ€™s
alpha</a>, seems toÂ suggest
we should wait a few more weeks.</p>

<p>Nevertheless,Â this topic got me thinking about which MLB teams are most
balanced (a lot of runs scored and few runs allowed, or, in other words,
solid hitting, pitching and fielding).</p>

<p>First, I looked into team OPS numbers:</p>

