  <li>The 17-28 Cubs post a record not at all reflective of
their run-differential.</li>
  <li>The Dâ€™backsÂ could use some pitching help.</li>
  <li>Though Colorado scores theÂ most runs in baseball (see discussion
above), they are still holding opponents to much fewer runs than
they score. Thus, seeing that they play their games in the same
ballpark as their opponent, this analysis bodes very well for
the Rockies.</li>
</ul>

<p>With all of this in mind, the most impressive teams thus far in terms of
<em>balance</em> (which is vital to sustained success in any sport) and the
ones that would seem to be in it for the long haul are:</p>

<ol>
  <li>Oakland</li>
  <li>Detroit</li>
  <li>San Francisco</li>
  <li>LA Angels</li>
  <li>Colorado Rockies</li>
</ol>

<p>You can of course interpret the data however youâ€™d like. These are my
five most balanced teams, as of now. Â Oaklandâ€™s season is off to an
